Mystics of free trade
From Cambridge — recently, I was invited to guest lecture in a globalization course taught by two colleagues at Harvard. "I must warn you."
One of them had previously reminded me, "These students are all strong supporters of globalization."
He once asked the students present in the first class to choose between free trade and import restrictions, and over 90 percent supported the former.
And that's before even introducing the magical effects of comparative advantage.
We know that if we asked the same question to a representative sample — not Harvard students — in a real survey, we would get a completely different result.
In the United States, the ratio of opponents to supporters of trade restrictions is 2:1.
But Harvard students' answers would not seem particularly surprising.
Because those with higher technology and better education tend to be more supportive of free trade than blue-collar workers.
Perhaps these Harvard students had already anticipated their future prospects and made their decisions accordingly.
Or perhaps they simply do not understand how trade works.
After all, when I met with them, I deliberately used a different approach to ask the same question and emphasized the potential distributional effects of trade.
The results showed that the consensus supporting fair trade disappeared completely, even more rapidly than I had anticipated.
At the beginning, I first asked everyone if they agreed that I would perform a particularly magical experiment.
I selected Nicholas and John as volunteers and told them that I had a way to make the $200 in Nicholas's account disappear — "Poof!" — while simultaneously adding $300 to John's account. The great achievement of social engineering could add an additional $100 value to the whole class as a unit.
Would they allow me to play this little trick?
Only a small portion of people firmly agreed with the result, many were indecisive, and even more opposed the implementation of this change.
Please provide the sentence you would like translated.
It's obvious that students can't tolerate this form of large-scale income redistribution, even if the overall economic cake has been expanded.
I then asked why most of them instinctively supported free trade, which in fact would lead to a similar — indeed, even a more significant — redistribution of wealth from losers to winners.
The students all seemed to be stunned.
I continued by saying, let's assume that Nicholas and John both started competing small businesses.
John works harder, saves and invests more, and produces better products. As a result, he not only has $300 more than Nicholas but also pushes Nicholas's company out of the market, causing a loss of $200 for Nicholas.
So how many students support this change?
This time, almost everyone voted in favor — in fact, only Nicolas disagreed!
I then proposed another hypothesis directly related to international trade.
If John pushed Nicholas out of the market by importing high-quality products from Germany?
Or outsourcing business processes to China, where labor rights are not yet fully established?
Or is it employing child labor in Indonesia?
The degree of agreement with this change decreases in the order of the options mentioned above.
In addition, technological innovation can also place certain people in a more disadvantaged position, just like trade. What is your stance on this?
Only a few students are willing to restrain the development of technology.
For almost everyone, the idea of banning the production of light bulbs to protect the job of candle makers is simply a foolish notion.
Therefore, what students are opposing is not necessarily redistribution itself, but rather certain specific forms of redistribution.
Like most of us, they also care about the fairness of the procedures.
If we are to judge the outcome of redistribution, we must know the objective circumstances that led to such an outcome.
We don't begrudge Bill Gates or Warren Buffett their immense wealth, even if some of their competitors have had difficult times, probably because they and their rivals all operate under the same basic rules and face extremely similar opportunities and challenges.
But if Gates and Buffett had become wealthy through fraud, breaking labor laws, damaging the environment, or exploiting subsidies from foreign governments instead of through their own intelligence and hard work, our views would be entirely different.
If we cannot tolerate redistribution achieved by violating widely accepted moral standards domestically, on what grounds can we justify it merely because it involves cross-border transactions?
Similarly, when we expect redistribution effects to eventually lead to equality in the long run, and thus benefit everyone in the end, we are likely not to care much about the transfer of income.
This is also why we believe that even though technology may bring short-term negative consequences for some people, it is still crucial to promote its development.
On the other hand, when trade continuously impacts the same group of people — low-skilled blue-collar workers — we become anxious about globalization.
But many economists have ignored these obvious differences.
They tend to attribute their worries about globalization to the foolish and selfish motives of trade protectionism or ignorance, without realizing that the most important issue at stake is actually a moral one.
Because these economists are unable to recognize that international trade sometimes—though certainly not often—leads to redistribution consequences that we cannot accept domestically, they are unable to appropriately engage in public discussions.
And if their arguments are morally indefensible, how can they strongly defend trade?
When globalization occasionally raises thorny issues related to the legitimization of redistribution effects, we should not reflexively respond by restricting trade.
There are many pros and cons that require difficult balancing, including the possibility that globalization may cause greater wealth deprivation for people in other places than for victims within the United States.
But democratic countries should have a more appropriate discussion on this issue and make more conscious and thoughtful decisions.
The approach that is overly enamored with globalization merely because it has made the cake bigger will, in the long run, erode the very legitimacy of globalization itself.
